Geospatial risk modeling - the case of crime

Ken Steif, PhD

October 27, 2019

1.1 Predictive Policing & geospatial risk models

Of the many public sector machine learning algorithms that you may have heard of, none garner more ire than the use case we’ll develop in this chapter - Predictive policing. Predictive Policing is a form of geospatial risk prediction that borrows the locational experience of crimes observed in the recent past and tests the extent to which those experiences generalize to places that may be at risk for crime despite a lack of reporting.

Law enforcement has significant resource allocation questions. In 2017, the Chicago Police Department recorded 268,387 incidents, which equates to 735 incidents per day on average. There is a clear need for an operational planning tool aimed at reducitng crime. Victims of crime and even those who live in fear of crime, incur real costs, physically, emotionally and financially. Crime can depress land values and hinder economic development. Crime can deter children from walking to school in the morning or families from enjoying an evening on their porch. Crime can be both the cause and the symptom of many significant socio-emotional and economic outcomes.

To counter these outcomes, police departments spend millions of dollars on training and equipment, including predictive anlaytics. Spending on law enforcement analytics was estimated to be (still researching this number) in 2018, which isn’t surprising given the costs of crime and how much administrative data is collected on phenomenon. There’s data on 911 calls and crime reports, arrest data, conviction data, GPS data from police cruisers, real time geospatial gunshot triangulation data, prison data, parole data, social network data on gang affiliations - and the list goes on.

With so much data, one might think predictive policing would be a public sector data scientist’s dream. In reality, most of these datasets are so biased that without an intense focus on model validation, most law enforcement use cases of predictive policing are unuseful. A useful predictive policing model is one which can predict explicit crime risk by way of meaningful risk factors without being biased by the implicit risk generated from biased policing interventions.

Let’s unpack this a bit. As we’ll learn below, these algorithms predict risk by regressing a crime outcome like burglary on built environment risk factors like blight. It may be that neighborhoods with certain environmental risk factors breed the behavior that leads to increasead crime. It may also be that people with a high propensity to commit crime or report it, select into high crime neighborhoods. This idea is called ‘selection bias’, and it is the most difficult hurdle to overcome in any social science research.

Selection bias is discussed far more often in the context of inferential statistics than in predictive modeling. What is the effect of good teachers on educational outcomes? What is the effect of college on future wages? What is the effect of crime on home prices? All of these questions suffer from selection bias. Parents select into certain school districts and schools conditional on their preference for education quality. Students select into college conditional on their education background and willingenss to pay. Criminals choose to pray on certain neighborroods based on their preception of risk and reward.

In other words, none of this selection happens at random and if the selection criteria goes unaccounted for in the model, it will fall into the error term. Let’s imagine that the unobserved selection criteria is the sytsematic over-policing of minority neighborhoods by police. Although a white and non-white neighborhood may share the same explict risk factors, such as blight, the non-white neighborhood may have more reported crimes due to the ‘reporting bias’ of police. In this chapter, burglary risk is predicted. The assumption is that there is less reporting bias in burglary relative to other crime types like drug crime, for instance. The hypothesis underlying the model is that risk is a function of exposure to environmental risk and protective factors. Blight and vacancy are often strong risk factors for crime. Churches, recreation centers and other community assets may be examples of factors that help communities project against crime. There is an important literature on the Broken Windows Theory that I need to add later.

Below spatial structure features are created that we hope can account for some of this selection bias, but if not, the result will be one set of errors unique to the white neighborhood and another unique to the non-white neighborhood. This was tested for in x.x.x as well. These disparities are important because of how the model informs resource allocation. Any algorithm that creates a police surveillance disparity along racial lines is at best, unfair, and at worse, unconstitutional. At the conclusion of this chapter, we’ll discuss important context at the intersection of model bias and resource allocation.

1.2 On the accuracy/generalizability tradeoff in geospatial risk prediction models

The principal motivation for geospatial risk prediction is the idea of ‘latent risk’. Crime is a relatively rare event and it may be happening at a greater rate than what is observe in the data. The goal of the model then, is to predict this latent risk by borrowing the experience of observed crimes and testing how well those experiences generalize to places where no crime has been observed. Assuming these predictions are ‘useful’, defined as generalizable across different community contexts, it may be possible to create a tool that Police can use to more efficiently allocate their limited resources across space.

Accuracy & generalizability is far more nuanced in this context relative to say home price or churn prediction. A model that is perfectly accurate is one where the predicted crime count equals the observed crime count and such a model would fail to identify areas at latent risk. This makes goodness of fit is very difficult to judge for geospatial risk prediction models. The goal is to achieve a useful accuracy that improves on the resource allocation better than the business as usual approach, while ensuring this accuracy generalizes appropriately.

This chapter is organized as follows. In the next section, a host of crime, risk and protective factor data is downloaded and wrangled directly from the Chicago Open Data website. Section 3 focuses on featuring engineering. Section 4 develops some new spatial structure features. Section 5 estimates and maps risk predictions, and Section 6 validates those predictions for accuracy and generalizability. Section 7 outlines the homework for this assignment.

  )
}

2.1 Data wrangling: Creating the fishnet

What is the appropriate unit of analysis for predicting crime risk? The answer to this question brings about a whole new set of scale problems. In the home price use case, the house was the obvious unit of analysis, because features internal to the home play an important role. Crime events like assault or burglary do not come with similar information - all we know is that a crime event happened here.

At what spatial unit then, is it sensible to predict crime? The first part of the answer should be informed by the resource allocation process. Many police departments divide the city into administrative areas to which centralized resources are provided but some measure of autonomy is allowed. How useful would a patrol allocation algorithm be with a single prediction for each Police Beat or District?

There are thousands of people living in the average Police Beat and tens or hundreds of thousands of people living in a single Police District. It’s doubtful that these areas would provide enough precision intelligence on where to patrol. Predicting crime across these discrete administrative units may also assume for instance, that crime risk varies significantly on either immediate side of two adjacent administrative areas, a clear instance of the MAUP.

In the code below, policeDistricts and policeBeats are downloaded and mapped.

policeDistricts <- 
  st_read("https://data.cityofchicago.org/api/geospatial/fthy-xz3r?method=export&format=GeoJSON") %>%
  st_transform(crs=102271) %>%
  dplyr::select(District = dist_num)
  
policeBeats <- 
  st_read("https://data.cityofchicago.org/api/geospatial/aerh-rz74?method=export&format=GeoJSON") %>%
  st_transform(crs=102271) %>%
  dplyr::select(District = beat_num)

bothPoliceUnits <- rbind(mutate(policeDistricts, Legend = "Police Districts"), 
                         mutate(policeBeats, Legend = "Police Beats"))
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = bothPoliceUnits) +
  facet_wrap(~Legend) +
  labs(title = "Police adminstrative areas, Chicago") +
  mapTheme()

Instead of thinking about crime risk as a phenomena that varies across administrative units, think of it as one that varies smoothly across space - similar to elevation. As we’ll discover, crime is clustered, and thus crime in one location is likely correlated with crime nearby. One might then assume that crime risk dissipates outward from concentrated crime hot spots much like how elevation ebbs and flows from mountain tops to valleys. The best way to represent such a smooth spatial surface is to aggregate point phenomena to a lattice of grid cells. The reader familiar with GIS will immediate recognize that this tends to be done with ‘Raster’-based techniques. For this exercise, our grid cells will be vector polygons.

We refer to this grid cell lattice as the fishnet and create it below first by downloading a neighborhood layer from your machine and projecting it. This layer omits O’Hare airport in the northwest of the city which would otherwise distort our analysis. st_make_grid is then used to create the fishnet with 500ft by 500ft grid cells. Finally, the grid cells and boundary are plotted.

Why do we choose a 500ft grid cell? We’ve discussed many times how scale is the most difficult hurdle to overcome in spatial analysis. Here we are imposing our own scale, which if done incorrectly, can negatively impact the analysis. There are three key concerns when choosing a grid cell size. First, as mentioned, are the grid cells appropriately sized given the resource allocation process? Are we going to target police resources to square blocks or neighborhoods? Second, does the distrubtion of crime counts by grid cell follow the theoretical distribution assumed by the algorithm used to predict (more on that in x.5.1). Finally, it’s always important to realize that the more grid cells to be analyzed in regression, the longer the computing time.

chicagoBoundary <- 
  st_read("C:/Users/kennethsteif/Desktop/spring_2017/theBook/riskPredictionChapter/chicago_Boundary.shp") %>%
  st_transform(crs=102271)

The codeblock below downloads the data and selects only those burglaries that are “forcible entry”. Some additional data wrangling is accomplished first by removing extraneous characters from the Location field with gsub. The resulting field is then converted to seperate fields of X and Y coordinates. Those fields are then made numeric, converted to simple features, projected, and duplicate geometries are removed with distinct.

burglaries <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2017/d62x-nvdr") %>% 
  filter(Primary.Type == "BURGLARY" & 
         Description == "FORCIBLE ENTRY") %>%
  mutate(x = gsub("[()]", "", Location)) %>%
  separate(x,into= c("Y","X"), sep=",") %>%
  mutate(X = as.numeric(X),
         Y = as.numeric(Y)) %>% 
  na.omit %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")%>%
  st_transform(102271) %>% 
  distinct()

2.2 Data wrangling: Joining burglaries to the fishnet

First, a new ‘counter’ field, countBurglaries is mutate for each burglary. aggregate joins burglaries to the fishnet using the sum operation to sum countBurglaries. A grid cell with no burglaries receives NA which the mutate converts to 0. Additionally, a random uniqueID is generated for each grid cell, as well as a random group cvID that can be used for cross-validation later in the analysis. Roughly 100 cvIDs are generated (round(nrow(burglaries) / 100)) to allow 100-fold cross validation below.

crime_net <- 
  burglaries %>% 
  dplyr::select() %>% 
  mutate(countBurglaries = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countBurglaries = ifelse(is.na(countBurglaries), 0, countBurglaries),
         uniqueID = rownames(.),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

Figure x.x maps the count of burglaries by grid cell, and the spatial structure of burglaries begins to take shape in the map below as the hotspots are immediately apparent.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countBurglaries)) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Count of Burglaires for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme()

2.3 Data wrangling risk factors

Now that the crime_net includes data on our dependent variable, burglary, the next step is download and wrangle a small set of risk factor features. We create a very simply model here, gathering a small number of features that help test the hypothesis that crime presence is a function of exposure to certain environmental characteristics. A typical analysis would likely require many more features.

Six risk factors are downloaded along with a neighborhood polygon layer. The data includes 311 calls for abandoned cars, street lights out, graffiti remediation, sanitation complaints and abandon buildings; as well as the location of retail stores that sell liquor to go.

Take note of the approach used to wrangle each dataset. Data is downloaded; year and coordinates are created and the latter converted to sf. The data is then projected and a Legend field is added that describes the risk factor. This allows them to be rbind into one dataset below to easily create small multiple maps.

3.1 Feature engineering - Count of features by grid cell

There are many ways to engineer features that test the exposure hypothesis. In this chapter, two such approaches are demonstrated. The first simply sums the number of a given risk factor points occuring in a given grid cell. This is done by binding together the individual risk factor layers; then spatial joining (st_join) the fishnet to each point. The outcome is a large point layer with a column for each fishnet uniqueID. The layer is then converted to a data frame with st_set_geometry.

The next step is to move from a long form layer of risk factor points with grid cell uniqueIDs, to a wide form layer of grid cells with risk factor columns. Note the results of grouping by grid cell uniqueID and risk factor Legend, then counting the number of points. The full_join adds the fishnet geometries and spread converts to wide form. The output, vars_net is useful for regression purposes.

This is fairly complex data wrangling strategy, and it will be helpful for you to run each line separately.

vars_net <- 
  rbind(abandonCars,streetLightsOut,abandonBuildings,
        liquorRetail, graffiti, sanitation) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  full_join(fishnet) %>%
  spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
  na.omit()

Now let’s map each count feature as part of a small multiple map. Note that each risk factor in vars_net has a different range (min, max). A normal ggplot would allow us to facet_wrap(~group, scales = "free") to create ‘free’ scales for each map. At this time, such functionality has not been ported to geom_sf. Instead, a function is used to loop through the creation of individual risk factor maps and compile (ie. grid.arrange) them into one small multiple plot.

vars_net.long is vars_net in long form. vars is vector of Variable names and mapList is an empty list. The loop says for for each Variable, i, in vars, create a map by filtering for Variable i and then add the map to mapList. Once all six risk factor maps have been created, do.call then loops through the mapList and arranges each map in the small multiple plot.

vars_net.long <- 
  vars_net %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -geometry, -uniqueID)

vars <- unique(vars_net.long$Variable)
mapList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  mapList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(vars_net.long, Variable == i), aes(fill=value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme()}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(mapList, ncol =2, top = "Risk Factors by Fishnet"))

Interestingly, this risk factors seem to illustrate slightly different spatial processes. Abandoned_Buildings are mainly clustered in South Chicago, while Abandoned_Cars are mostly in the north. 311 complaints for Graffit tends to cluster along major thoroughfares and Liquor_Retail is heavily clustered in “The Loop”, Chicago’s downtown. In x.4.2, we’ll test the correlation between these features and burglaries.

3.2 Feature engineering - Nearest neighbor features

By counting risk factor events by grid cell, the exposure hypothesizes is tested at a very rigid scale and such a framework opens us up to all sorts of possible MAUP bias. As before, average nearest neighbor distance is likely a better approach for understanding local exposure to risk factors. The function calculates nearest neighbor distance.

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
      as.data.frame(nn) %>%
      rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
      gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
      group_by(thisPoint) %>%
      summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
      dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
      pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

Below, average nearest neighbor features are created for the six risk factor variables with k = 3. These features are created by converting vars_net polygon grid cells to points, then measuring average nearest neighbor distance. Note, the nn_function requires both input layers to be points. For demonstration purposes k is set to 3, but in a real model, one would want to test many different k definitions of scale.

vars_net$Abandoned_Buildings.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(abandonBuildings), 3)
    
vars_net$Abandoned_Cars.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(abandonCars), 3)
    
vars_net$Graffiti.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(graffiti), 3)
    
vars_net$Liquor_Retail.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(liquorRetail), 3)

vars_net$Street_Lights_Out.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(streetLightsOut), 3)
    
vars_net$Sanitation.nn =
    nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(sanitation), 3)

The nearest neighbor features are then plotted below. Note the use of select and ends_with to map only the newly generated nearest neighor features. Clearly, this approach considers expsosure at a different scale then simply counting up risk factor events by grid cell.

vars_net.long.nn <- 
  vars_net %>%
  dplyr::select(ends_with(".nn")) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -geometry, -uniqueID)

vars <- unique(vars_net.long.nn$Variable)
mapList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  mapList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(vars_net.long.nn, Variable == i), aes(fill=value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme()}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(mapList, ncol =2, top = "Nearest Neighbor risk Factors by Fishnet"))

final_net <-

Finally, neighborhood name and policeDistrict is spatially joined to the final_net using grid cell centroids. Note that some grid cell centroids do not fall into a neighborhood, returning NA, which is then removed with na.omit. Other neighborhoods are so small, they are only represented by one grid cell.

4.1 Exploring the spatial structure of burglary

In this section, the local spatial structure of burglary (by grid cell) is quantified and visualized by way of a statistic called Local Moran’s I. x.4.2 then tests the correlation between these and other features and countBurglaries.

Chapter x explored the Global Moran’s I in home prices - a measure of spatial autocorrelation. Here, the goal is to examine spatial autocorrelation on a local scale. While the null hypothesis for Global Moran’s I is that the count of burglaries is randomly distributed across the study area, the null hypothesis for Local Moran’s I is that burlgary count at a given location is randomly distributed relative to its immediate neighbors.

Like its global cousin, a spatial weights matrix is used to relate a unit to its neighbors. In Chapter X, a nearest neighbor weights matrix was used. Here, weights are calculated by way of polygon adjacency. The code block below create a neighbor list, poly2nb, and the spatial weights matrix, final_net.weights, using queen continguity, meaning that every grid cell is realted to its eight adjacent neighbors. Figure x.x below visualizes one grid cell and its queen neighbors. Any one grid cell’s neighbors can be returned with final_net.nb[[1457]]. `

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(final_net, queen=TRUE)
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = slice(final_net, 1483, 1484,1485, 1456, 1458,1429,1430,1431), fill = "red") +
  geom_sf(data = slice(final_net, 1457), fill = "black") +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, fill = NA) +
  labs(title = "Example of 'Queen' contiguity") +
  mapTheme()

The purpose of the visualization below is describe the spatial process of interest. final_net.localMorans is created by cbinding together final_net with the results of a localmoran test. The inputs to the test including the outcome of interest, countBurglaries and the spatial weights matrix. Several useful test statistics are output including I, the p-value and Significiant_Hotspots, defined as those grid cells with p-values <= 0.05. The data frame is then converted to long form for mapping.

Another grid.arrange loop is used to create a small multiple map of the aforementioned indicators. The legend in Figure x.x below, shows that very high values of I represent strong and statistically significant evidence of local clustering. This test certainly provides insight on the scale and intensity of the burglary spatial process.

final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(
    as.data.frame(localmoran(final_net$countBurglaries, final_net.weights)),
    as.data.frame(final_net, NULL)) %>% 
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(Burglary_Count = countBurglaries, 
                  Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                  P_Value = `Pr(z > 0)`) %>%
    mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.05, 1, 0)) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)
  
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme()}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Burglary"))

A generalizable model is one which will have to predict equally as well in the hotspots as the coldspots. In other words, a model fit only to the coldspots, will underfit to the hotspots. A model fit only to the hotspots will overfit the coldspots. As we saw with home prices, our hypothesis is that these spatial structure features will lead to more accurate and more generalizable predictions. Let’s see how new features can be engineered to best capture the local spatial structure.

Below, Local Moran’s I is calculated in the final_net. A dummy variable is created with ifelse to denote that a significant cluster, isSig, is defined as one with a p-value <= 0.0000001. In this instance, the goal is to find clusters that are far more significant than 0.05. Then, burglary.isSig.dist measures distance from each grid cell to its nearest significant cluster. The result is mapped in the figure below. This distance feature makes some significant assumptions about the local spatial process - namely that burglaries dissipate in a linear fashion from burglary ‘hotspots’ outward. The analyst could consider a whole host of way to model this trend with different significance thresholds, significance nearest neighbors and beyond.

final_net <-
  final_net %>% 
  mutate(burglary.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(final_net$countBurglaries, 
                                            final_net.weights)[,5] <= 0.0000001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(burglary.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                                           st_coordinates(st_centroid(
                                             filter(final_net, burglary.isSig == 1))), 1 ))

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = final_net, aes(fill = burglary.isSig.dist)) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Distance to highly significant local burglary hotspots") +
  mapTheme()

5.1 Poisson Regression

Take a look at the distribution of countBurglaries in the histogram before. Unlike home prices which were normally distributed (like a bell curve), the distribution burglaries is far more skewed. This should be intuitive, given that crime is a relatively rare event. When data is distributed in this way, an OLS regression is inappropriate. In this section, we learn and demonstrate Poisson Regression, uniquely suited to modeling an count outcome like countBurglaries.

ggplot(final_net, aes(countBurglaries)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of burglary by grid cell")

The choice of algorithm, poisson or otherwise, is a function of the data and the use case. We could recode the burglary data to a binomial outcome suited for logistic regression, where 0 means no burglaries in a grid cell and 1 means more than 0 burglaries. This would give a prediction intepreted as the ‘probability of a burglary being committed here’. 73% of grid cells have at least 1 burglary, which would render most areas as having a high probability. Regressing on a count outcome is useful because it predicts a more continuous quantity of risk.

Of course, for a given algorithm to be effective, the observed data must be distributed according to the assumptions of the algorithm. For OLS, that means having an outcome that is normally distributed. For logistic regression, the assumption is that probabilities are well fit to the logistic ‘S curve’. A simulated Poisson distribution is plotted below. Does it appear similar to the observed distribution in Figure X.x above?

5.2 Cross-validated poisson Regression

Unlike previous chapters, we are not going to split the final_net into training and test sets. Moving directly to cross-validation is a much more useful approach to guaging generalizability in these models. House prices partially rely on aspatial features like number of bedrooms, but geospatial risk models are purely spatial in nature. This means that we can perform spatial cross-validation to guage generalizability

A well generalized crime predictive model must predict equally as well in all communities and a geospatial model that predicts equally well in all neighborhoods is one which can learn crime risk patterns that apply at both Citywide and local spatial scales. The local scale is particularly difficult to model, because the burglarly experience in one place may only be unique to that one place. The best way to ensure that the model has learned both the global and local dynamics, is to hold out one local area, train the model on the remaining n - 1 areas and then predict for the held out area. We refer to this approach as Leave-one-group-out cross-validation (LOGO-CV).

Three final_net fields can be used for cross-validation. A random generated cvID associated with each grid cell can be used for random k-fold cross-validation. Neighborhood name and police District can be used for spatial cross-validation.

Goodness of fit metrics will be generated for both random k-fold and LOGO cross validations for two different specifications (4 total regressions). The first includes Just Risk Factors features and are listed in reg.vars below. The second includes both the risk factors plus the Spatial Structure features created in x.4.1. These are listed in reg.ss.vars.

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn", "loopDistance")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", "Liquor_Retail.nn", 
                 "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn", "loopDistance", 
                 "burglary.isSig", "burglary.isSig.dist")

The crossValidate function below is a very stripped down version of Caret’s train function. It takes an input dataset; a cross-validation id; a dependentVariable and a list of independent variables, indVariables. cvID_list is a list of unique ids which could be numbers or neighborhood name, for instance. For a given iteration, For given neighborhood name, the function assigns each grid cell not in that neighborhood to the training set, fold.train, and each cell in that neighborhood to the test set, fold.test. A model is trained from the former and used to predict on the latter. The process is repeated until each neighborhood has a turn acting as a hold out. The output is a simple features data frame with a Prediction for each grid cell. For now, the countBurglaries variable is hardwired into the function, which you will have to change when you do your homework.

crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {

allPredictions <- data.frame()
cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])

for (i in cvID_list) {

  thisFold <- i
  cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")

  fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  
  regression <-
    glm(countBurglaries ~ ., family = "poisson", 
      data = fold.train %>% 
      dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
  
  thisPrediction <- 
    mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
  allPredictions <-
    rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}

The code block below runs crossValidate to estimate four different regressions that are then compared below. reg.cv and reg.ss.cv perform random k-fold cross validation using Just Risk Factors and the Spatial Structure features, respectively. reg.spatialCV and reg.ss.spatialCV perform LOGO spatial cross validation using the aforementioned two groups of features.

The function makes it easy to swap out different cross-validation group ids. k-fold cross validation uses the cvID. LOGO uses the neighborhood name. You may also wish to explore results using the Police Districts. Note, in the select operation at the end of the LOGO-CV models, the cross validation id is standardized to cvID.

reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countBurglaries",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countBurglaries, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countBurglaries",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countBurglaries, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countBurglaries",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countBurglaries, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countBurglaries",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countBurglaries, Prediction, geometry)

As we’ve done in previous chapters, mean error and mean absolute error (MAE) can be calculated on predicted and observed crime counts, then compared across models. Because generalizability in these models is arguable more important than accuracy, below, the latter will be evaluated in the context of the former.

5.3 Generalizability by neighborhood context

Now we get down to the important question of whether these algorithms can perpetuate racial bias. In x.1.1 we discussed how systematic over-policing of certain communities may lead to a reporting or selection bias, and if left unaccounted for, this variation will fall into the error term of the regression. If this reporting bias falls along racial lines, then the resulting predictions may exasperate racist policing practices and have a disparate impact on communities of color.

This proposition is tested in this section. Below tidycensus is used to pull race data by Census Tract. percentWhite is calculated and tracts are split into two groups, Majority_White and Majority_Non_White. A spatial subset is used to get tracts within the study area.

6.1 Does this model allocate better than traditional crime hotspots?

Police departments the world over have moved to hot spot policing, targeting police resources to the places where crime is most concentrated. Do risk predictions outperform traditional ‘kernel density’ hotspot mapping? Below we create Kernel Density hotspots maps, like the one visualized in Figure x.x. Hotspot maps make certain assumptions about the spatial relationships of the point phenomena they are derived from. The best way to think about a hot spot map is that it ‘makes predictions’ based purely on spatial autocorrelation.

Kernel Density works by centering a smooth kernel or curve over each point, such that the kernel is at its highest directly over the point and the lowest at the range of a circular search radius. The value of the kernel density in a particular place is the sum of all the kernels that underlie it. Thus, areas that have many points in close proximity will have relative densities. The key scale assumption in a kernel density is the specification of a global search radius. Below, kernel density built from three different search radii are shown.

library(raster)
burg_ppp <- as.ppp(st_coordinates(burglaries), W = st_bbox(final_net))
burg_KD.1000 <- spatstat::density.ppp(burg_ppp, 1000)
burg_KD.1500 <- spatstat::density.ppp(burg_ppp, 1500)
burg_KD.2000 <- spatstat::density.ppp(burg_ppp, 2000)
burg_KD.df <- rbind(
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(burg_KD.1000), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "1000 Ft."),
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(burg_KD.1500), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "1500 Ft."),
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(burg_KD.2000), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "2000 Ft.")) 

burg_KD.df$Legend <- factor(burg_KD.df$Legend, levels = c("1000 Ft.", "1500 Ft.", "2000 Ft."))

ggplot(data=burg_KD.df, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_raster(aes(fill=layer)) + 
  facet_wrap(~Legend) +
  coord_sf(crs=st_crs(final_net)) + 
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  mapTheme()

The code block below creates a kernel density with a 1000 foot search radius. as.ppp converts the burglary coordinates to a ppp class unique to the spatstat package. The density function creates the kernel density. To map the results, the ppp is converted to a data frame and then an sf layer. Points are spatially joined to the final_net and the mean density is taken. Here density is visualized with a sample_n of points overlayed on top.

burg_ppp <- as.ppp(st_coordinates(burglaries), W = st_bbox(final_net))
burg_KD <- spatstat::density.ppp(burg_ppp, 1000)

as.data.frame(burg_KD) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(final_net)) %>%
  aggregate(., final_net, mean) %>%
   ggplot() +
     geom_sf(aes(fill=value)) +
     geom_sf(data = sample_n(burglaries, 1500), size = .5) +
     scale_fill_viridis() +
     mapTheme()

Next, a goodness of fit indicator is created to illustrate whether the risk predictions capture more of the observed burglaries relative to the kernel density. If the predictions do capture more observed burglaries, then the risk predictive model provides more robust targeting tool for allocating police resources. Here are the steps.

  1. Compute the kernel density; and aggregate to the fishnet.
  2. Scale the kernel density to run from 1-100 and then reclassify those values into 5 risk categories.
  3. Join to that, the count of burglaries for each grid cell.
  4. Repeat for the risk predictions.
  5. Count the rate of test set points by model type and risk category. Map and plot accordingly.

Below, the needed components for kernel density are computed.

# Compute kernel density
burg_ppp <- as.ppp(st_coordinates(burglaries), W = st_bbox(final_net))
burg_KD <- spatstat::density.ppp(burg_ppp, 1000)
# Convert kernel density to grid cells taking the mean
burg_KDE_sf <- as.data.frame(burg_KD) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(final_net)) %>%
  aggregate(., final_net, mean) %>%
#Mutate the Risk_Category field as defined below.
  mutate(label = "Kernel Density",
         Risk_Category = ntile(value, 100),
         Risk_Category = case_when(
           Risk_Category >= 90 ~ "90% to 100%",
           Risk_Category >= 70 & Risk_Category <= 89 ~ "70% to 89%",
           Risk_Category >= 50 & Risk_Category <= 69 ~ "50% to 69%",
           Risk_Category >= 30 & Risk_Category <= 49 ~ "30% to 49%",
           Risk_Category >= 1 & Risk_Category <= 29 ~ "1% to 29%")) %>%
#Bind to a layer where test set crime counts are spatially joined to the fisnnet.
  bind_cols(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(burglaries) %>% mutate(burgCount = 1), ., length) %>%
    mutate(burgCount = replace_na(burgCount, 0))) %>%
#Select the fields we need
  dplyr::select(label, Risk_Category, burgCount)

Finally, the rate of burglary points by risk category and model type is calculated and plotted. What we would hope to see is that the risk predictions capture a greater share of observed burglary events in the highest risk category relative to the kernel density. The very simple model created here narrowly edges out the kernel density in the highest risk category.

rbind(burg_KDE_sf, burg_risk_sf) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(countBurglaries = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Rate_of_test_set_crimes = countBurglaries / sum(countBurglaries)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Rate_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE)

6.1 Conclusion

In this chapter, a geospatial risk prediction model was developed to borrow the burglary experience in places burglary has been observed, and test whether that experience generalizes to places where the risk is ‘latent’. Spatial cross-validation was introduced to test generalizability. It is easily the most constrained generalizability test employed thus far. We also learned a host of new spatial structure variables that successfully predicted the local burglary hot spots.

Evaluating the usefulness of a geospatial risk prediction algorithm in a resource allocation context is perhaps more difficult then any other goodness of fit concept covered in this book. If identifying latent risk is the goal (areas at risk for crime despite none being reported), then accuracy becomes less important than generalizability. A useful model then is one that is 1) more accurate than the current decision making process and 2) equally as such for areas across the City.

Burglary was chosen as the outcome of interest because we assume that it is reported with less bias compared to other crimes, like drug crime. Reporting bias could come from victims (un)willingness to call the police, or from police themselves systematically over-policing certain communities. The issue with reporting bias is that it feeds broader concerns over selection bias. It may be that criminals are selecting into areas with certain risk factors or that reporters of crime exhibit some unobserved selection criteria on which crimes to report.

There are other crimes, and other geographic events that may exhibit more or less selection bias. Many cities are collecting 311 data on grafitti. It could be that grafitti is only happening where it’s actually being reported, or that would-be reporters selectively choose where to report grafitti based on community social norms. Conversely, it’s harder to argue that a reporting or selection bias exists for building fires. It’s hard to consider an example where a building fire isn’t reported to a fire department.

Predictive policing is likely the most established machine learning use case in the public sector. Again, this is likely because of the high costs associated with crime and the need for police departments to engage in operational planning. Many of the more robust predictive policing solutions return not only placed-based predictions but time/space predictions. The model described here is easily extendable to time/space with the inclusion of time interval (15, 30, 60 minutes etc.) fixed effects. In the next chapter, we will focus on these time/space effects considering generalizability across both.

One final thought for you to consider. Let’s imagine for a moment that we could predict with 100% certainty where and when crime will occur. How would you effectively deploy such an algorithm into patrol cars? Is it reasonable to assume that your average police officer wants to learn predictive modeling or even understand it’s motivations? Is reasonable to assume that an officer, who relies everyday on his or her accured experience, would ignore their intuition in favor of a notification that pops up on an tablet in their cruiser?

This book is heavily focused on analytics, but deploying those analytics to help someone make a ‘better’ decision is equally as important. The more entrenched the decision-making process, the harder it may be to change. This is where dashboarding, user interface design and user experience design come in to play. The algorithm is only step 1. The more effectively one can design an interface that compliments, not replaces a user’s lived experience, the easier it will be to get stakeholder buy-in.
